## Metaprompting for Failure Modes

When a turn doesn't perform well, ask Codex how to improve its own instructions:

```
That was a high-quality response, thanks! It seemed like it took a while to finish though.
Is there a way to clarify your instructions so you can get to a response as good as this faster next time?
It's extremely important to be efficient — users won't get the most out of them in time.

Please:
1. Read through your instructions starting from [section]
2. Identify anything that may have caused you to take longer than needed
3. Write targeted (but generalized) additions/changes/deletions to make similar requests faster with the same quality
```

When metaprompting, generate responses a few times and pay attention to common elements across runs — some suggestions will be too specific to that situation, so generalize before applying.

**Common failure modes:**
| Symptom | Targeted fix |
|---|---|
| Slow to start / overthinking | Ask it to propose changes that reduce time-to-first-tool-call |
| Loggy, unnatural status updates | Ask it to rewrite the user-updates section to match your preference |
| Repetitive preamble tics ("Got it—", "Aha", "Good catch") | Ask it to propose replacements that sound more like natural pair programming |

Create an eval to measure whether each prompt change is actually an improvement for your use case before shipping it.
